<paragraph blockId="20.[151,1437,1230,2013]" pageId="20" pageNumber="21">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,349,1446,1472]" pageId="20" pageNumber="21">Recognition.</emphasis>
This long setose species is distinguished from other species by a distinctively shaped epandrium, with a deep subapical ventral notch and rounded ventral expansion, straight phallus and apex of the hypandrium forked with spine-like lateral projections (
<figureCitation box="[622,752,1518,1545]" captionStart="FIGURES 21–25" captionStartId="19.[151,264,1787,1811]" captionTargetBox="[184,1429,195,1746]" captionTargetId="figure-17@19.[151,1436,181,1763]" captionTargetPageId="19" captionText="FIGURES 21–25. Male terminalia of Iteaphila with unbranched R 4+5. 21, I. beringiensis sp. nov., lateral view; 22, I. bifida sp. nov., lateral view, with arrow indicating apex of phallus in posterior view; 23, I. recta sp. nov., lateral view; 24, I. tribulosa sp. nov., lateral view; 25, same, apex of hypandrium, posterior view. Scale bar = 0.1 mm. Abbreviations: cerc—cercus; epand— epandrium; epand brg—epandrial bridge; hypd—hypandrium; ph—phallus; sur—surstylus." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4745586" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4745586/files/figure.png" pageId="20" pageNumber="21">Figs 24, 25</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
